On 3 March, the National Science Review published a paper on the origin and continued evolution of SARS-CoV-2. The corresponding authors are Lu Jian (bioinformatics center, School of Life Sciences, Peking University) and Cui Jie (Shanghai Pasteur Institute, Chinese Academy of Sciences) .

Based on the analysis of molecular evolution of the novel coronavirus genome, two subtypes, L and S, have been discovered, which are widely distributed in different regions and in different populations.

Based on the way the COVID-19 evolved, the authors speculate that there may be significant differences in the transmission capacity and severity of the disease between the two subtypes.

The difference between the two subtypes is that at 28144 of the viral RNA genome, the L is the t base (corresponding to Leucine, LEU) and the s is the C base (corresponding to serine, Ser) . Compared with other coronaviruses, the authors found that the s type new coronaviruses were more closely related to the bat-derived coronaviruses in the evolutionary tree, leading to the conclusion that the s type was relatively older.

The corollary is that the relatively old s type coronaviruses should have produced more strains because they had more time to circulate in people. But the genomic data showed that l type accounted for 70% and s type accounted for 30% , and each l type strain carried relatively more new mutations than s type. The authors analyzed why the relatively young l coronaviruses produced more strains, speculating that they spread more or replicate more rapidly in humans, which may mean they are more virulent.

In addition, the authors found that the virus strains isolated from most of the patients indicated that they were infected with only one subtype of the L or s forms. L isoforms were more prevalent in the early stages of Wuhan outbreak, but due to strong human intervention, the frequency of l isoforms decreased after early January 2020.

However, a strain isolated from an American patient who had traveled to Wuhan before the diagnosis suggests that it may have contracted both the L and s forms of the new coronavirus (though the possibility of a new mutation can not yet be ruled out) . Follow-up work will need to expand the sample size to test these conclusions or assumptions, the authors write.
